            <p>This is a neatly communicated letter addressing the important challenge facing early career researchers (ECRs), a secure transition to academic and research career. It is built on the reflections of researchers from a European Commission (EC) funded project, undertaken across various European countries. The outcomes are largely targeted at the EC level and how it can play a role in ensuring a career path for ECRs. Citing various examples, of which there are plenty, it highlights the precarious nature of transition faced by ECR&#x2019;s as a result of their limited contracts, in their most vulnerable career stage. They are still learning research skills and still building experience forging their academic career, when they eventually face the abrupt step of ensuring the next long-term contract. Too often they are unprepared to obtain their own grant, especially with the competition for limited opportunities. This inevitably has, and is highlighted by the authors, apart from financial, mental wellbeing consequences. This is unfortunately a reality shared globally, with similar cases for example in the UK and USA. The letter is aimed at the EC, a major funder, to act as a leader in ensuring ECR research trajectory continues. The proposal suggested rightly focuses on support at the beginning, whilst still in the early career project, and once near the finish. A few points and suggestions the authors could elaborate or discuss are presented as follows.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Considering the first of the three stages suggested, support in the early stage of the career is crucial in building the skills and confidence needed in a research career. The focus on building a formal structure on training and mentorship is well made. There are examples of this being undertaken by multiple institutions elsewhere too. For e.g. UK Research and Innovation body (UKRI) has recently introduced Doctoral Training Partnerships (
                <ext-link ext-link-type="uri"
                      xlink:href="https://www.ukri.org/what-we-do/developing-people-and-skills/esrc/doctoral-training-partnerships/">https://www.ukri.org/what-we-do/developing-people-and-skills/esrc/doctoral-training-partnerships/</ext-link>), which not only train ECR&#x2019;s in various skills from the perspective of a broader inter-university and research partner collaboration. The key with such approach is having a coordinating body. Although the suggestion of assigning confidential advisors (&#x2018;Ombuds&#x2019; or mentors is suggested in the letter, the need for a formal structure within the projects would be necessary to realise the desired support outcomes. It is crucial who and where the advisor(s) sit and how they operate. It is also important to specify how the Ombuds will collaborate within projects. The letter rightly emphasises on Ombuds being familiar with diversity and inclusion principles. This is especially even more challenging across a wide network of different countries as would be anticipated in EC countries. Ensuring a ring-fenced budget for capacity building is an excellent idea, but it is crucial national governments and institutions, ensure existence and continuity of such advisory and training work. So this should be potentially a requirement before EC grants are awarded. A suggestion on how such structure can be created and maintained hence would be a good discussion point.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Considering support whilst during the grant in the form of inclusion in decision-making and leadership is rightly made. However, this probably is broad issue, which will inevitably deal with research culture and ethics. Recently a lot has been discussed including an excellent paper by (
                <ext-link ext-link-type="uri"
                      xlink:href="https://journals.plos.org/ploscompbiol/article?id=10.1371/journal.pcbi.1006914">Maestre et al, 2019</ext-link>). However, to ensure practicality, it might have to be supported via individual institutions and nations as well. For example, a wider recognition of good culture could be considered such as a charter or concordat which institutions sign up (e.g. UK&#x2019;s 
                <ext-link ext-link-type="uri"
                      xlink:href="https://www.universitiesuk.ac.uk/topics/research-and-innovation/concordat-support-research-integrity">concordat for research integrity</ext-link> or the 
                <ext-link ext-link-type="uri"
                      xlink:href="https://www.advance-he.ac.uk/equality-charters/athena-swan-charter">Athena Swan Charter</ext-link>). Recognition for institutions that demonstrate good support on such initiatives, could then be used as an additional criteria by the EC when considering funding bids. The key thing is good culture of supporting ECR&#x2019;s should be practically assessed and become a motivating factor for institutions bidding for EC funds.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Considering the latter part of an ECR&#x2019;s involvement in a project and the next step, a network of ECR&#x2019;s will be crucial and is well pointed at. Good examples are provided and may be stronger case could be made in the letter, how this should be well-established and embedded within projects. Discussion could be made if there a case to be made for an independent EC funded body working across projects.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Overall an engaging and well written letter, with clear ideas on how to support ECR&#x2019;s. It will be rewarding to have EC and national bodies take steps to ensure the future of researchers.</p>
